"""
mkt-context | leviticus | ch 26-27
Covenant blessings and curses (ch.26), vows and valuations (ch.27).
Historical/cultural context: Hittite suzerainty treaty structure (preamble/stipulations/
blessings/curses); sevenfold escalating curses; land Sabbaths during exile (→ 2 Chr 36:21);
covenant formula "walk among you" (v.12, cited 2 Cor 6:16); ANE vow valuations as
labor-market prices; herem (devoted things); tithes; sanctuary shekel standard.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-leviticus-26-27.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS = {
  "26": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 26 is the covenant enforcement chapter of Leviticus — its structural function is parallel to Deuteronomy 27-28. Biblical scholars have identified a formal parallel with second-millennium BCE Hittite suzerainty treaties, which followed a fixed structure: (1) preamble identifying the great king, (2) historical prologue, (3) stipulations, (4) provision for deposit and reading, (5) list of divine witnesses, (6) blessings for compliance, (7) curses for violation. Leviticus 26 provides the blessings (vv. 3-13) and curses (vv. 14-39) that complete the treaty structure begun in Exod 19-24. The opening prohibition against idols and sacred pillars (<em>matsevah</em>) is the stipulation that precedes the enforcement clauses.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Sabbath observance and sanctuary reverence are the two bookend obligations that frame the chapter. They are the positive covenant obligations whose violation will trigger the curse sequence. The Sabbath represents the temporal dimension of Israel's covenant identity; the sanctuary represents the spatial dimension. Both are given as the minimal positive requirements before the blessings and curses are announced.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The conditional structure: <em>im beḥuqqotai telekhú</em> (if you walk in my statutes) — the blessing sequence is conditional on covenant obedience. 'Walk' (<em>halakh</em>) is the Torah's standard metaphor for life-conduct: obedience as a sustained journey, not a series of discrete acts. The blessings (vv. 4-13) cover the full range of human flourishing: agricultural abundance, safety, military success, population growth, and YHWH's presence.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The first blessing: reliable rainfall (<em>geshmeihem be'ittam</em>, your rains in their season). Agricultural life in the ancient Levant was entirely dependent on rainfall — there was no irrigation comparable to Egypt's Nile agriculture. The autumn and spring rains (the former and latter rains) determined the annual harvest. Rainfall as a covenant blessing presupposes the rain-god theology of Canaan (Baal was the storm-deity); YHWH claims direct sovereignty over the rain that Baal was supposed to control.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Abundance so overwhelming that threshing continues until grape harvest and grape harvest continues until sowing — an agricultural cornucopia where one harvest overlaps the next. The image is of surplus that cannot be consumed before the next harvest begins. This hyperbolic abundance language appears in ANE blessing formulae — the idealized picture of a fertile land under divine favor. Amos 9:13 uses nearly identical language as an eschatological promise.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>shalom</strong> in the land: the comprehensive well-being that comes from covenant faithfulness. The <em>shalom</em> blessing includes safety from wild animals (<em>vehashiboti ḥayyah ra'ah min-ha'arets</em>) and from military threat. The removal of dangerous animals from the land is a significant promise — lions, bears, and other predators were real threats in the ancient Levant. Archaeological evidence confirms the presence of lions in Israel into the Persian period.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Military blessing: enemies fleeing before Israel. The reversal of normal military ratios — five chase a hundred (v. 8) — is a familiar motif in Israel's conquest narratives. The blessing operates on the principle that covenant faithfulness gives a military advantage that cannot be explained by human military strength. Gideon's 300 against the Midianites (Judg 7) and David's victories over Goliath exemplify this principle.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Five chasing a hundred, a hundred chasing ten thousand — the geometric multiplication of military effectiveness. The hundredfold increase (5:100 = 1:20; 100:10,000 = 1:100) reflects escalating divine amplification. The numbers are symbolic rather than literal — the point is the complete reversal of natural military odds when YHWH fights for Israel. Deut 32:30 uses similar language ('one could chase a thousand').</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>ufaniti aleikhem</strong>: 'I will turn/face you.' YHWH's personal attention is the foundational blessing — the divine face turned toward Israel rather than away. The covenant formula: <em>vahafareti etkhem vehirbeiti etkhem</em> (I will make you fruitful and multiply you) echoes the creation blessing (Gen 1:28) and the Abrahamic promise (Gen 17:2). YHWH's covenant-renewal is explicitly connected to the original creation and Abrahamic blessing patterns.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The surplus of previous harvests still present when the new harvest comes — a sign of abundance so great that storage space becomes the limiting factor. Clearing out old produce to make room for new is a luxury problem, presupposing that the granaries have not been emptied by famine, war, or taxation. The blessing of surplus is historically concrete: in the ancient world, food reserves meant survival through drought years.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>venatati mishkani betokheikhem</strong>: 'I will set my dwelling (<em>mishkan</em>) among you.' The ultimate blessing is divine presence — YHWH dwelling (<em>shakan</em>) in the midst of Israel. <em>Mishkan</em> (tabernacle) is the noun form of <em>shakan</em>; YHWH's promise here is to make the tabernacle permanent by his ongoing choice to remain present. <em>Velo-tig'al nafshi etkhem</em>: 'I will not abhor you' — the negative formulation of divine acceptance, ruling out the possibility of YHWH withdrawing in disgust from Israel.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>vehithallakhti betokheikhem vehayiti lachem lElohim ve'atem tihyu li le'am</strong>: 'I will walk among you and will be your God, and you shall be my people.' The covenant formula in its fullest OT expression — the bi-directional relationship statement that defines the covenant. <em>Vehithallakhti betokheikhem</em> (I will walk among you) is YHWH's personal presence in the community, not merely in the tabernacle. Paul quotes this verse in 2 Cor 6:16 to identify the church as the new temple of the living God — the walking-among-you presence is now the indwelling Spirit.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Historical grounding of the covenant relationship: the Exodus from Egypt as the foundational act of covenant-making. <em>Asher hotse'ti etkhem me'erets Mitsrayim me'avet lahem</em> (who brought you out of Egypt, from being their slaves). The broken yoke bars (<em>vatishbor motot 'uvvekhem</em>) is the image of liberation — the wooden yoke-bars that slaves carried are broken by YHWH. This Exodus-grounding is the basis of all covenant obligation throughout the Torah.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The curse section begins with the same conditional structure inverted: <em>ve'im lo tishme'u li</em> (but if you do not listen to me). Four curse cycles follow (vv. 14-17, 18-20, 21-22, 23-26, 27-39), each introduced by Israel's continued non-response and YHWH's escalating response. The repetitive structure of the curses is deliberate — it mimics treaty-violation escalation protocols found in ANE treaties.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The language of spiritual contempt: <em>tim'asu et-ḥuqqotai</em> (despise my statutes), <em>ve'im et-mishpatai tiqqa'el nafsheikhem</em> (if your soul abhors my rules). The progression from non-compliance (v. 14) to active contempt is significant — the curse intensifies as Israel's rejection becomes more deliberate. The treaty-violation framework treats covenant contempt as the most serious escalation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>First curse cycle: sudden terror (<em>behala</em>), wasting disease (<em>shaḥefet</em>), fever (<em>qaddaḥat</em>), loss of agricultural productivity, military defeat. The terror, disease, and failed harvests are recognizable catastrophes — not supernatural inventions but the historical consequences of political instability and defeat. The phrase <em>veakhlu otam oyveikhem</em> (your enemies shall eat what you grow) is a brutal image of the defeated providing food for their conquerors.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>venatati panai bakhem</strong>: 'I will set my face against you' — the opposite of v. 9's <em>ufaniti aleikhem</em>. The divine face set against Israel is YHWH's active opposition, not merely withdrawal of favor. Military reversal: enemies rule over Israel, Israel flees from those who do not pursue. The psychological dimension of curse — <em>venastem ve'en-rodef etkhem</em> (you shall flee when no one pursues) — captures the paranoid vulnerability of a defeated people.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The sevenfold escalation formula: <em>veyasafti leyassar etkhem sheva al-ḥattoteikhem</em> (I will punish you seven times more for your sins). Seven is the completion/intensification number — sevenfold punishment means escalation to the maximum. This formula appears four times (vv. 18, 21, 24, 28), creating four cycles of escalation. The repetition makes the chapter's structure unmistakable: each cycle of non-repentance triggers a more severe response.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The agricultural curse escalates: the sky becomes iron (<em>shemei khem kabarzel</em>) and the earth bronze (<em>ve'arsekhem kinḥusha</em>) — metaphors for absolute drought and infertility. Iron sky cannot be penetrated by prayer or rain; bronze earth cannot be broken by the plow. This agricultural curse is the most devastating possible in an agrarian society — it means total crop failure and starvation.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>vetam lariiq koḥakhem</strong>: 'your strength shall be spent in vain.' The irony of futile labor — all the effort of farming produces nothing when the land refuses to yield. The agricultural curse converts Israel's hard work into meaninglessness. This is the economic analogue of the military flight of v. 17: all activity is wasted, all effort meaningless.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Second escalation: if Israel continues walking contrary (<em>baqeri</em>, in hostility/contrariness) to YHWH, YHWH will also walk contrary to them with another sevenfold blow. The term <em>qeri</em> (contrariness/hostility/stubbornness) used for Israel's stance and then for YHWH's response is a deliberate mirror: YHWH meets Israel's obstinacy with equal obstinacy. This is the covenant's enforcement mechanism — the relationship becomes adversarial.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Wild animals as divine agents: YHWH releases predatory animals (<em>behemat hasadeh</em>) against Israel, bereaving them of children, destroying livestock, reducing the population until the roads are empty. This is the reversal of the blessing in v. 6 (removal of dangerous animals). The same land that was promised to be free of dangerous animals becomes overrun by them when Israel breaks the covenant.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The pattern repeats: Israel fails to be disciplined (<em>velo tivasseru li</em>, you did not accept discipline from me) and continues in contrariness. The curse structure requires Israel's repeated failure to respond — YHWH does not jump to maximum punishment but escalates gradually. This graduated response implies that repentance at any stage would halt the progression.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Third escalation: YHWH himself walks contrary to Israel with sevenfold punishment. The personal pronoun <em>va'ani</em> (and I myself) intensifies the divine involvement — YHWH is not merely allowing disaster but actively inflicting it. The covenant relationship has inverted from mutual walking-together (v. 12) to mutual walking-against.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The sword of covenant vengeance (<em>ḥerev noqemet neqam-berit</em>, sword that executes covenant vengeance). The sword as agent of covenant enforcement is attested in ANE treaties — curses often invoked the sword of the great king against a vassal who broke the treaty. Here YHWH is the great king whose sword enforces the covenant. Plague (<em>dever</em>) is sent within cities when people gather there for safety.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Famine: ten women baking bread in one oven — the collapse of agricultural economy has reduced grain so severely that ten households share a single oven's worth of fuel and bread. <em>Veheshivu laḥmekhem bamishqal</em> (they will dole out your bread by weight) — bread rationed by weight is an extreme scarcity image. Egyptian records document bread rationing during periods of famine.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Fourth and final escalation: despite all this, if Israel still does not listen but walks contrary, YHWH will walk contrary in anger. The fourth cycle is the most severe — the accumulated refusal to respond to three previous cycles of escalating punishment reaches its terminal point. The phrase <em>beḥamat qeri</em> (in fury of contrariness) combines the emotional register (fury/<em>ḥemah</em>) with the relational register (contrariness/<em>qeri</em>).</p>",
    "28": "<p><em>Va'ani elaikh beḥemet qeri veyissarti etkhem af-ani sheva al-ḥattoteikhem</em>: 'I will walk contrary to you in wrath, and I myself will discipline you seven times for your sins.' The final sevenfold blow is now preceded by divine anger rather than mere action — the emotional escalation marks this as the final stage before complete destruction. The curses that follow (vv. 29-38) describe total societal collapse.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Cannibalism: eating the flesh of sons and daughters. This was a documented reality of ancient sieges — the siege of Jerusalem in 70 CE was recorded by Josephus as producing exactly this horror. The prophet Jeremiah applied Lev 26:29 to the Babylonian siege (Jer 19:9). The inclusion of cannibalism in the curse list is not rhetorical exaggeration but historical anticipation of what extreme siege conditions produce.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Destruction of the high places (<em>bamot</em>) and incense altars (<em>ḥammanim</em>) — the apparatus of Canaanite syncretism that Israel was warned against. YHWH will destroy what Israel built for false worship. <em>Venatatim al-pigglei gillo'leikhem</em> (I will cast your dead bodies on the lifeless forms of your idols) — the dead bodies of Israel scattered on their idol-altars is an image of ultimate humiliation: the idols they worshipped cannot save them.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The sanctuary itself (<em>miqdasheikhem</em>) will be desolated and YHWH will not smell the pleasing aromas of offerings. This is the reversal of every offering blessing in Leviticus 1-7: the entire sacrificial system becomes inoperable. The refusal to smell (<em>lo arim bereiaḥ niḥoaḥakhem</em>) reverses the <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> (pleasing aroma) formula that confirmed acceptance of every offering. The temple and sacrifice were the means of YHWH's presence; their desolation means complete divine withdrawal.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The land will be desolated so severely that even foreign enemies who settle in it will be appalled. The enemies' appallment (<em>veshamevu aleiha oyveikhem</em>) serves as a witness to the extent of YHWH's judgment — it is so complete that even those who benefited from Israel's dispossession are horrified by what they inherited. The Assyrian resettlement of Samaria (2 Kgs 17:24-26) and the Babylonian period in Judah partially fulfill this description.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Scattering among the nations (<em>ufizareti etkhem baggoyim</em>) and the sword pursuing Israel. The Diaspora as covenant curse — the covenantal homeland is lost, and Israel becomes a refugee people in foreign lands. The land left desolate and the cities destroyed: this is the template for the Assyrian destruction of Israel (722 BCE) and the Babylonian destruction of Judah (586 BCE) that later prophets interpreted through exactly this lens.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>az tirtsé ha'arets et-shabbetoteiha kol-yemei hashammah</strong>: 'Then the land shall enjoy its sabbaths all the days that it lies desolate.' The land gets its unpaid Sabbath rests during the exile. The Chronicler (2 Chr 36:21) explicitly applies this verse to the 70-year Babylonian exile: the land rested for 70 years to make up for 490 years of missed Sabbaths (approximately from Solomon's time to the exile). This calculation reflects the connection between Israel's covenant unfaithfulness and the land's Sabbath-deprivation.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The land's Sabbath rest during desolation is explicitly described as compensatory: all the days it lies desolate it has the rest it was denied during Israel's occupancy. The passive construction — 'it shall have rest' — treats the land as a moral agent with legitimate claims. The land's Sabbath rights are protected even when Israel forfeits its own rights. This anthropomorphic treatment of the land is unique to the Holiness Code's land theology.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The psychology of the exile survivors: YHWH puts fear in their hearts in enemy lands, so that even the sound of a windblown leaf makes them flee. The paranoid terror (the reversal of military courage in v. 7-8) is both punishment and testimony — the people who could not be disciplined by external catastrophe are undone by internal fear. The sound of a leaf (<em>qol ale nidaf</em>) as a terror-trigger is a powerful image of the completely demoralized people.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The survivors stumble over one another fleeing from a sword that is not there — the military inversion is complete. At the blessing stage, five chase a hundred; at the curse's nadir, a hundred flee from no one. <em>Lo-tihyeh lachem teqomah lifnei oyveikhem</em>: 'You shall have no power to stand before your enemies.' The military incapacity completes the reversal of every blessing in vv. 6-8.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Perishing among the nations and being consumed by enemy land. The curse reaches its ultimate expression: Israel as a people ceases to exist in their own land and is absorbed by the nations they were sent among. This is the outer edge of the curse — national dissolution, the end of the covenant people as a political entity. The prophets repeatedly refer back to this threat when warning Israel and Judah.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The survivors rot away in their iniquity (<em>yimmaqu ba'avonam</em>) in enemy lands — not a quick death but a slow dissolution. They rot in the iniquities of their fathers as well as their own: intergenerational guilt. The image of rotting carries both physical and moral resonances — the community decomposes in exile as it decomposed morally in the land.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The pivot: restoration begins with confession (<em>vehitvaddu et-avonam</em>). The covenant can be restored if Israel confesses both their own iniquity and that of their fathers — acknowledging the generational pattern of faithlessness. The confession addresses the full scope of the curse: as the curses accumulated through generations, so the confession must cover the generational dimension. This is the model for Ezra's (Ezra 9) and Nehemiah's (Neh 9) restoration confessions.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The uncircumcised heart (<em>levavam he'arel</em>) — the heart that has not submitted to YHWH, the inner covenant sign lacking. When this heart is humbled (<em>az yikna levavam he'arel</em>), it corresponds to the circumcision of the heart that Deut 30:6 promises YHWH will perform in the restoration. The connection between exile, heart-humbling, and heart-circumcision is the background for Paul's argument about circumcision of the heart in Rom 2:29.</p>",
    "42": "<p><strong>veZakharti et-briti Ya'aqov ve'af et-briti Yitsḥaq ve'af et-briti Avraham ezkor</strong>: 'I will remember my covenant with Jacob, and I will remember my covenant with Isaac, and I will remember my covenant with Abraham.' YHWH's covenant memory is the basis of restoration. The reverse order (Jacob, Isaac, Abraham) emphasizes the historical trajectory — the most recent patriarch first, the first patriarch last, but all three equally in YHWH's memory. The divine memory of covenant is the ground of hope for exiled Israel.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The land must make up its Sabbaths — even during the restoration process, the land's Sabbath claim is maintained. The people's exile was not punishment only; it was also the land's relief. The restitution logic works in both directions: Israel must acknowledge their abandonment (<em>ya'anu et-avonam</em>, they shall make amends for their iniquity) while the land gets its compensatory rest.</p>",
    "44": "<p><strong>ve'af-gam-zot bihyotam be'erets oyveihém lo-me'asti'im velo-ge'altim lekhallotam</strong>: 'Yet for all that, when they are in the land of their enemies, I will not reject them or abhor them so as to destroy them completely.' The most remarkable verse in the chapter: despite all the curses, YHWH refuses to abandon Israel entirely. <em>Lekhalotam</em> (to destroy them completely) is what will not happen — not because of Israel's merit but because of YHWH's covenant commitment. This is the foundation of Jewish survival through exile, diaspora, and destruction.</p>",
    "45": "<p>YHWH remembers the covenant with the forebears (<em>briti rishonim</em>) — the original Exodus generation whose covenant defines Israel's identity. The phrase <em>asher hotse'ti otam me'erets Mitsrayim le'einei haggoyim</em> (whom I brought out of Egypt in the sight of the nations) recalls the public, witnessed nature of the Exodus: YHWH's covenant-keeping in the restoration will be equally public, equally a testimony to the nations. The Exodus as prototype of all future redemption.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The closing colophon of Leviticus's legislative core: <em>elleh haḥuqqim vehamishpatim vehatorah</em> (these are the statutes, rules, and law) established by YHWH at Mount Sinai. The three-term legislative vocabulary (<em>ḥuqqim</em>, <em>mishpatim</em>, <em>torah</em>) encompasses all forms of divine legislation. The Sinai location grounds the entire Levitical system in the covenant-making event. Chapter 27 is an appendix to this colophon, addressing a specific topic (vows) separately.</p>"
  },
  "27": {
    "1": "<p>Chapter 27 is an appendix to Leviticus, addressing the redemption of vowed persons and property. It may have been added after the formal colophon of 26:46 because vow-law required its own framework. The chapter deals with situations where persons or property have been dedicated (<em>neder</em>, vowed) to YHWH and then need to be redeemed through monetary payment. The system assumes a basic principle: anything dedicated to YHWH has a cash-equivalent value that allows it to be reclaimed through payment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The special vow (<em>neder</em>) involving the valuation of persons (<em>be'erkekha nefashot laYHWH</em>). A person might vow themselves or a family member to YHWH's service — probably for sanctuary service under the Levites. The valuation system allows the person to remain at home by paying a redemption price. The standardized price table (vv. 3-7) reflects an attempt to create a fair, predictable system across different economic classes and demographics.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The standard valuation table for vowed persons: male 20-60 = 50 shekels, the highest valuation. This is the peak productive-labor period for males in an agricultural society. The valuations are not statements about human worth but about labor-market value — the economic contribution a person in that demographic category would typically make. The sanctuary shekel (v. 25) was the standard unit: 50 shekels was a substantial sum — roughly equivalent to a year's wages for a skilled laborer in the ancient Near East.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Female 20-60 = 30 shekels. The lower female valuation reflects the lower market value of female labor in the ancient Israelite economy, not a theological statement about women's worth. The text offers no theological rationale; it simply reflects contemporary economic realities. Numbers 3 and 4 describe women serving at the tabernacle in various capacities, indicating that women could be valuably dedicated to sanctuary service.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Youth (5-20 years): male 20 shekels, female 10 shekels. The lower valuations for the youth category reflect both lower labor productivity and longer remaining dependency period. A 10-year-old male contributes less to an agricultural household's immediate productivity than a 30-year-old male, hence the lower redemption value.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Infancy (1 month to 5 years): male 5 shekels, female 3 shekels. The lowest valuations — infants and small children are economically dependent, not contributors. The inclusion of infants in the vow-valuation system suggests that parents did occasionally vow infants to YHWH's service (as Hannah vowed Samuel, 1 Sam 1:11) and the redemption option was available for those who later chose to reclaim the child.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Old age (60+): male 15 shekels, female 10 shekels. The valuations drop for those past peak productive age, reflecting declining labor capacity. Notably, older women are valued at 10 shekels (the same as young girls) while older men drop to 15 (less than half the peak male value). The elderly retain economic value in an agricultural household through accumulated experience and skilled crafts.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The poverty accommodation: if the vowing person cannot afford the standard valuation, the priest assesses their ability and sets a proportionate price. The priest's flexible assessment ensures the vow system is accessible to all economic levels — the wealthy pay the standard price; the poor pay what they can. This graduated approach is consistent with the graduated offering scales throughout Leviticus.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Vowed animals that may be offered to YHWH (clean animals from the permitted categories) become holy and cannot be redeemed — whatever is given to YHWH is absolutely his. The principle <em>kol asher yitten mimenu laYHWH yihyeh qodesh</em> (whatever is given to YHWH shall be holy) establishes the irrevocability of acceptable-animal vows. Unlike persons and unclean animals, a vowed sacrificial animal cannot be replaced or reclaimed.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The exchange prohibition: no substitution of an equivalent or different animal once vowed. If substitution is attempted, both the original and the substitute become holy — the attempted exchange backfires and costs double. This provision prevents the natural human tendency to upgrade vowed animals (promising a fat animal, delivering a lean one) or to reclaim an animal by substituting a less valuable one.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Vowed unclean animals (those not eligible for sacrifice) are assessed by the priest — they cannot be offered but can be redeemed for their monetary value. The unclean animal vow creates an anomaly: the animal cannot go to the altar but the person has dedicated it. The priest's valuation provides the mechanism for converting the vow into a cash equivalent that can be applied to the sanctuary.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The priest's assessment is authoritative — <em>ka'asher yaarekh hakohen ken yihyeh</em> (as the priest values it, so it shall be). The priest functions as an objective third-party appraiser, ensuring the assessed value reflects market reality rather than the vow-maker's self-interest. The priestly appraisal system is the ancient world's equivalent of independent professional valuation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The redemption option for vowed unclean animals: pay the assessed value plus a fifth (<em>ḥomesh</em>). The 20% surcharge on redemptions appears throughout ch. 27 (vv. 13, 15, 19, 27, 31) as a consistent redemption fee. The surcharge ensures that redemption costs more than the original commitment — it prevents the system from being used to temporarily park assets with YHWH and then reclaim them at no cost.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A vowed house is assessed by the priest as good or bad quality — its value is objectively determined, not self-reported. The house-vow system allowed a person to donate real property to the sanctuary while retaining the option to redeem it. Archaeological evidence shows Israelite houses varying enormously in size and construction quality from a single room to multi-room compounds — the priest's quality assessment was necessary to set a fair value.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Redemption of a vowed house: the assessed value plus the one-fifth surcharge. The right of redemption makes the vow system flexible — vows are not irrevocable gifts but formal commitments with a built-in buy-back option at a premium. This flexibility encouraged generosity (people could vow without fear of permanent loss) while the surcharge maintained the seriousness of the commitment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Vowed inherited field (ancestral land): the valuation is based on its seed capacity — how much grain it produces per cycle, measured in <em>homer</em> of barley seed. A homer of barley seed was equivalent to roughly 220 liters — the valuation is 50 shekels per homer's worth of seed capacity. This seed-based valuation system tied the field's worth to its agricultural productivity rather than arbitrary market price.</p>",
    "17": "<p>If dedicated in a jubilee year, the field's full value applies — the entire productive cycle from jubilee to jubilee remains. This is the maximum value: the field will produce crops for the full 49-year cycle before reverting to its original owner at the next jubilee. The jubilee system intersects directly with the vow system — the field's value is always calculated relative to the remaining jubilee cycle.</p>",
    "18": "<p>If dedicated after the jubilee, the priest calculates the proportionate remaining years — the value decreases as fewer productive years remain before the next jubilee. The pro-rated valuation is a sophisticated actuarial calculation: the field's value in the vow system declines as the jubilee approaches, exactly as the field's market value would decline in a system where all land reverts at jubilee.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Redemption of a vowed field: assessed value plus the fifth. The surcharge applies consistently to all redemptions throughout ch. 27. If the person who vowed the field wants it back, they pay more than its assessed value — the 20% premium is the cost of reneging on the commitment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>If the vowed field is not redeemed or has been sold to another person, it may no longer be redeemed. The irrevocability kicks in when the field changes hands — once sold by the sanctuary to a third party, the original vow-maker's redemption right is extinguished. The sanctuary's property rights are protected against an original owner trying to reclaim through a third-party sale.</p>",
    "21": "<p>At jubilee, the unredeemed vowed field becomes <em>ḥerem</em> to YHWH and passes to the priests. <em>Ḥerem</em> (devoted/under the ban) is the term for something irrevocably belonging to YHWH that cannot be redeemed or sold — the opposite of the standard vow with its redemption option. The field's jubilee status as priestly inheritance means it becomes permanently attached to the Levitical landholding system.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Purchased (non-ancestral) field: a person can also vow a field they bought rather than inherited. The purchased field has a different legal status than the ancestral field — it reverts to the original owner at jubilee anyway, not to the vow-maker. The vow-valuation for a purchased field is calculated for the jubilee remainder only, since the field's permanent ownership is already determined.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The priest calculates the assessed value to the jubilee year; the vow-maker pays the assessed amount as holy to YHWH on that day. The immediate payment (<em>bayom hahu</em>, on that day) prevents deferred payment that might become default. The sanctuary receives the cash value of the purchased field's remaining years rather than the field itself, which will revert to its original landowner at jubilee.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The jubilee reversion of the purchased field to the original owner confirms that the purchased field was never truly the vow-maker's to give permanently. The jubilee principle — land ultimately belongs to YHWH and only to Israel as tenants (Lev 25:23) — constrains what can be permanently donated to the sanctuary.</p>",
    "25": "<p>All valuations use the sanctuary shekel (<em>sheqel haqqodesh</em>): 20 gerahs to the shekel. The sanctuary shekel was the standard unit of weight for all cultic transactions — it may have been a slightly heavier shekel than the commercial shekel, ensuring the sanctuary received full weight. Standardized weights were a persistent problem in the ancient world; the sanctuary shekel represents an attempt to create a reliable standard for sacred transactions. Archaeological finds of stamped weights from the Iron Age confirm weight standardization was practiced in Israel.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Firstborn animals are excluded from the vow system — they already belong to YHWH (Exod 13:2; 34:19-20). You cannot vow what you do not own. The firstborn principle is one of the oldest covenant obligations in the Torah: the first product of the womb belongs to YHWH, whether animal or human (human firstborns are redeemed). The exclusion from vow-making reflects the prior claim YHWH has on all firstborns.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Unclean firstborns (those from species not eligible for sacrifice) may be redeemed at the assessed value plus the fifth — or if not redeemed, sold at the assessed value. The unclean firstborn cannot go to the altar but must still be handled through the sanctuary's economic system. The redemption plus surcharge maintains the consistent 20% premium across all redemption contexts.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>akh-kol-ḥerem asher yaḥarim ish laYHWH</strong>: 'But no devoted thing (<em>ḥerem</em>) — anything that a man irrevocably devotes to YHWH — shall be sold or redeemed.' The <em>ḥerem</em> category is the absolute counterpart to the standard vow: while standard vows can be redeemed (with surcharge), <em>ḥerem</em> devotion is completely irrevocable. Everything devoted under <em>ḥerem</em> is most holy to YHWH and cannot return to human use. This is the principle applied to Jericho (Josh 6:17-19) and to the destruction of Canaanite nations (Deut 7:2, 20:16-17).</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>Ḥerem</em> applied to persons: any person irrevocably devoted (<em>ḥerem</em>) cannot be ransomed — he shall surely be put to death (<em>mot yumat</em>). This is the most severe application of the <em>ḥerem</em> principle: what belongs to YHWH absolutely cannot be reclaimed. The contexts for human <em>ḥerem</em> in the OT are primarily warfare (captive enemies devoted to destruction) and capital offenses (Achan's violation of Jericho's <em>ḥerem</em>, Josh 7:15). The verse is not a mechanism for arbitrary human sacrifice but for the execution of those placed under formal covenant ban.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The tithe (<em>ma'aser</em>) — every tenth of the land's produce, seed, and fruit trees — is holy to YHWH. The tithe is described as <em>qodesh laYHWH</em> (holy to YHWH), establishing it as a category alongside the sanctuary shekel and the firstborn. The tithe system had multiple layers in the Torah: a Levitical tithe (Num 18:21-24), a festival tithe (Deut 14:22-27), and a poor tithe (Deut 14:28-29). Leviticus 27 establishes the base principle that a tenth belongs to YHWH.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Tithe redemption: a person may redeem their agricultural tithe by paying its assessed value plus the fifth surcharge. The 20% premium applies here as throughout ch. 27. The redemption option for the agricultural tithe allowed households to convert the tithe from produce to cash — practical for those distant from the sanctuary or with perishable surplus.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Livestock tithe: every tenth animal that passes under the shepherd's rod. The method — counting animals sequentially and dedicating every tenth one regardless of quality — prevents the tithe-payer from selecting the worst animals for YHWH. The rod-counting method (also attested in later rabbinic practice) removes human judgment from the selection: the tenth one is the tenth one, whether healthy or lame.</p>",
    "33": "<p>No quality-selection for the livestock tithe — the counted tenth is given regardless. If a substitution is attempted (exchanging a better for a worse, or worse for better), both the original tenth and the substitute become holy. The same anti-substitution rule as for vowed sacrificial animals (v. 10): attempted evasion doubles the commitment rather than reducing it.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The final verse of Leviticus: <em>elleh hamitsvot asher tsivvah YHWH et-Moshe el-bnei Yisrael behar Sinai</em>: 'These are the commandments that YHWH commanded Moses for Israel on Mount Sinai.' The colophon closes the entire book with the Sinai authority formula. Leviticus begins with YHWH calling to Moses from the completed tabernacle (1:1) and ends with all the commandments traced back to Sinai — the book's legislative authority rests on both the ongoing presence (tabernacle) and the founding revelation (Sinai).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, LEVITICUS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'leviticus', c)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
